article.description: The Phoenix Mercury's Plenette Pierson and Penny Taylor were too much for San Antonio to handle.
article.headline: Pierson scores 20 in rout
article.linkText: Pierson, Mercury blast Silver Stars by 32
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Mercury's Plenette Pierson and Penny
Taylor were too much for San Antonio to handle.

Pierson scored a season-high 20 points and Taylor had 16 points
and nine rebounds -- one rebound shy of her second straight
double-double -- to help the Mercury snap a five-game losing streak
with an 87-55 rout of the Silvers Stars on Wednesday.

"We wanted to make them guard our inside players," Taylor
said. "Plenette got so many points in the first half being
aggressive, so they had to worry about her."

Diana Taurasi had 19 points, six rebounds and four assists as
the Mercury (9-12) scored a season-high and improved on last year's
WNBA-low eight wins.

Taurasi, the No. 1 pick in the draft, made her first six shots
and finished 9-for-12. Taylor was 7-of-9 and Pierson 6-of-9, good
for a combined 73.3 percent.

"We shot the ball exceptionally well," Mercury coach Carrie
Graf said. "I think that was a big part of it. But ultimately the
way we attacked the rebounding was huge. That allowed us to get our
running game going."

Adrienne Goodson and Agnieszka Bibrzycka had 12 points each and
LaToya Thomas had 10 for the Stars (6-16). San Antonio has lost
seven of its last eight.

The game was the first for the teams since Phoenix traded
All-Star center Adrian Williams to the Stars for Gwen Jackson on
Monday. Williams had a team-high eight rebounds but went scoreless.
Jackson had eight points and six rebounds.

"It was great seeing my old teammates, but I'm a Silver Star
now, and we're just trying to get the season back on track,"
Williams said.

The Mercury outrebounded San Antonio 40-20 and were never
threatened after a 14-0 run late in the first half. Taurasi's
jumper started the run, which ended on a 3-pointer by Taylor for a
39-24 lead with 2:40 remaining in the half.

"They just outworked us," Stars coach Dee Brown said. "That
was an old-fashioned butt-kicking right there."

The Mercury led 46-30 at halftime.

"The was a big game for us," Taurasi said. "This one was
important for our confidence."
